          Programming note: Money Stuff is going to be off for a few weeks =
starting tomorrow. I planned this before Elon Musk tried to cancel his Twit=
ter deal, and I am not a monster, so there will be occasional columns as Mu=
sk or other news require. But it will not publish every day; we=E2=80=99ll =
resume normal service sometime in August.

 =20
   =20
      Cake
   =20
 =20

Not much is going on today, so=C2=A0I thought we might talk about=C2=A0an i=
nteresting Delaware Chancery Court decision=C2=A0from last April. In March =
2020, a private equity fund, Kohlberg & Co.,=C2=A0signed a merger agreement=
 to buy a company called DecoPac Holdings Inc., which =E2=80=9Csells cake d=
ecorations and technology to supermarkets for use in their in-store bakerie=
s,=E2=80=9D in a=C2=A0$550 million leveraged buyout. Kohlberg also got comm=
itment letters from lenders to provide debt financing for the deal.
Then=C2=A0the Covid-19 pandemic got worse,=C2=A0the supermarket-cake-decora=
ting business declined, and Kohlberg =E2=80=9Clost their appetite for the d=
eal shortly after signing it.=E2=80=9D So, as the judge =E2=80=94 then-Vice=
 Chancellor=C2=A0Kathaleen McCormick =E2=80=94 writes, =E2=80=9Cthe buyers =
called their litigation counsel and began evaluating ways to get out of the=
 deal.=E2=80=9D
They came up with three approaches:
=09They said that DecoPac had experienced a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effec=
t=E2=80=9D due to the decline in its business during the pandemic. If there=
 was an MAE, then Kohlberg could terminate the agreement.=09They said that =
DecoPac had not complied with its covenant to =E2=80=9Coperate the Business=
 in the Ordinary Course of Business,=E2=80=9D because it had done unusual=
=C2=A0things (like draw on a revolver) to respond to the pandemic. If DecoP=
ac breached its covenants, then Kohlberg could terminate.=09They took steps=
 to blow up their financing, sending exaggeratedly bad projections to their=
 lenders along =E2=80=9Cwith demands for more favorable debt financing term=
s.=E2=80=9D Asked for better financing for a worse deal, the lenders declin=
ed, and Kohlberg did not get its financing. This is important because the c=
ontract allowed DecoPac to seek specific performance, that is, ask a Delawa=
re court to order Kohlberg to pay the $550 million and close the deal, but =
only if =E2=80=9Cfull proceeds of the Debt Financing have been funded to Bu=
yer.=E2=80=9D By blowing up the debt financing, Kohlberg planned to avoid s=
pecific performance: Even if the court didn=E2=80=99t believe it about the =
MAE or covenant stuff, it wouldn=E2=80=99t order Kohlberg to close the deal=
 if the debt financing wasn=E2=80=99t available.

So Kohlberg canceled the deal and DecoPac sued. The vice chancellor was not=
 amused by Kohlberg=E2=80=99s excuses:

At trial, the plaintiffs proved that DecoPac did not breach the MAE represe=
ntation, given the durational insignificance and corresponding immaterialit=
y of the decline in sales. They also proved that, even if it was reasonable=
 to expect that these sales declines would give rise to an MAE, the seller-=
friendly exception for events =E2=80=9Crelated to=E2=80=9D government order=
s applied, and DecoPac had not suffered disproportionately to comparable co=
mpanies. The=C2=A0plaintiffs likewise demonstrated that DecoPac operated in=
 the ordinary course of business in all material respects. The plaintiffs f=
urther proved that the buyers breached their obligation to use reasonable b=
est efforts in connection with the debt financing.
Adding another layer of complication to the analysis, the buyers claim that=
, despite these holdings, it need not close. They rely on a contractual exc=
eption to the parties=E2=80=99 agreement conditioning the seller=E2=80=99s =
right to specific performance on fully funded debt financing. Because there=
 is no debt financing in place, the buyers argue that the court may not gra=
nt specific performance. The court disagrees. Applying the prevention doctr=
ine, this decision deems the debt financing condition met because the buyer=
s contributed materially to lack of debt financing by breaching their reaso=
nable-best-efforts obligation.
Chalking up a victory for deal certainty, this post-trial decision resolves=
 all issues in favor of the seller and orders the buyers to close on the pu=
rchase agreement.

On specific performance in particular, she wrote:

=E2=80=9CA party seeking specific performance must establish that (1) a val=
id contract exists, (2) he is ready, willing, and able to perform, and (3) =
that the balance of equities tips in favor of the party seeking performance=
.=E2=80=9D This court has not hesitated to order specific=C2=A0performance =
in cases of this nature, particularly where sophisticated parties represent=
ed by sophisticated counsel stipulate that specific performance would be an=
 appropriate remedy in the event of breach.
Here, the parties stipulated to the remedy of specific performance, but tha=
t stipulation applies =E2=80=9Cif and only if . . . the full proceeds of th=
e Debt Financing have been funded to Buyer on the terms set forth in the [D=
CL] to fund the payment of the Estimated=C2=A0Closing Payment at Closing (o=
r would be funded at the Closing if the equity Financing is substantially c=
ontemporaneously funded at the Closing)=E2=80=9D (the =E2=80=9Cdebt-funding=
 condition=E2=80=9D).
Kohlberg moved to dismiss Plaintiffs=E2=80=99 claim for specific performanc=
e on the basis of the debt-funding condition, arguing that Plaintiffs=E2=80=
=99 claim for specific performance is barred because it is undisputed that =
the full proceeds of the Debt Financing were not funded. ...
At trial, Plaintiffs demonstrated that Kohlberg=E2=80=99s breach of Section=
 6.15(a) contributed materially to Kohlberg=E2=80=99s failure to obtain Deb=
t Funding. Plaintiffs proved that each of the Lenders were willing to execu=
te Debt Financing on the terms of the DCL and that Kohlberg refused to move=
 forward. In the words of one of the Lenders, when Kohlberg made the Financ=
ing Demands, =E2=80=9Cthey changed the ask and risk profile of the deal and=
 were not willing to adjust the economics, so they were really looking for =
a way out.=E2=80=9D The non-occurrence of Debt Financing, therefore, was du=
e materially to Kohlberg=E2=80=99s failure to move forward toward a final c=
redit agreement on the terms of the DCL.

The deal closed in May 2021,=C2=A0a few weeks after her decision; I guess K=
ohlberg figured out its financing.
Anyway I know I am late to it but I hope you enjoyed this digression into t=
he recent history of Delaware M&A litigation. McCormick was a vice chancell=
or at the time of this opinion; she is now the chancellor,=C2=A0the chief j=
udge of the Delaware court that hears basically all high-stakes merger liti=
gation in the US. It will be interesting to see what she does next.

