      Oh fine, fine fine fine, fine
   =20
 =20

Here=E2=80=99s a letter from Twitter Inc.=E2=80=99s lawyers=C2=A0to Elon Mu=
sk=E2=80=99s lawyers about their merger agreement:

Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s and the other Musk Parties=E2=80=99 purported terminatio=
n is invalid and wrongful, and it constitutes a repudiation of their obliga=
tions under the Agreement. Contrary to the assertions in your letter, Twitt=
er has breached none of its obligations under the Agreement, and Twitter ha=
s not suffered and is not likely to suffer a Company Material Adverse Effec=
t. The purported termination is invalid for the independent reason that Mr.=
 Musk and the other Musk Parties have knowingly, intentionally, willfully, =
and materially breached the Agreement, including but not limited to Section=
s 6.3, 6.8, and 6.10 thereof. The Agreement is not terminated, the Bank Deb=
t Commitment Letter and the Equity Commitment Letter remain in effect, and =
Twitter demands that Mr. Musk and the other Musk Parties comply with their =
obligations under the Agreement, including their obligations to use their r=
espective reasonable best efforts to consummate and make effective the tran=
sactions contemplated by the Agreement (including by taking all steps neces=
sary to obtain a favorable outcome under the United Kingdom=E2=80=99s Natio=
nal Security and Investment Act 2021), the Bank Debt Commitment Letter, and=
 the Equity Commitment Letter. As it has done, Twitter will continue to pro=
vide information reasonably requested by Mr. Musk under the Agreement and t=
o diligently take all measures required to close the transaction.
Twitter reserves all contractual, legal, and other rights, including its ri=
ght to specifically enforce the Musk Parties=E2=80=99 obligations under the=
 Agreement.

Twitter=E2=80=99s lawyers are Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen & Katz; disclosure, I=
 worked there a long time ago. If you=E2=80=99re following along at home, w=
hen Wachtell says =E2=80=9CMr. Musk =E2=80=A6 breached =E2=80=A6 Sections 6=
.3, 6.8, and 6.10,=E2=80=9D that is a shorthand way of saying that Musk has=
 not been using his reasonable best efforts to get the deal closed (section=
 6.3), has not been doing his best to get his financing finalized (section =
6.10), and has been making all sorts of disparaging public announcements wi=
thout consulting with Twitter (section 6.8). None of this is exactly surpri=
sing. I have nothing really to say about this letter that I did not say  ye=
sterday or  Saturday =E2=80=94=C2=A0this letter is just a placeholder until=
 Twitter can sue =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I guess I have to mention it.
In other news, we talked a bit yesterday about how Musk=E2=80=99s banks wil=
l be relieved if he gets out of the deal, because their $13 billion debt fi=
nancing commitment is pretty underwater. Paula Seligson and Davide Scigliuz=
zo at Bloomberg News  have more on that:

Banks had promised that the riskiest Twitter buyout debt -- $3 billion of u=
nsecured bonds to be rated CCC, the lowest rung of junk -- would cost no mo=
re than about 11.75%. That compares to a market average of about 13.6% on c=
omparably-rated bonds, up from 9.9% when the deal was announced, according =
to data compiled by Bloomberg. ...
At a fixed 11.75% coupon, and assuming an eight-year maturity, banks sellin=
g the unsecured bonds today would have to offer a discounted price of about=
 91 cents on the dollar to reach an all-in yield of about 13.6%. That would=
 result in a loss of between $150 million and $200 million, net of underwri=
ting fees banks typically earn for selling unsecured debt.


