   =20
      Stock?
   =20
 =20

One weird aspect of Musk=E2=80=99s quasi-terminated deal to buy Twitter=C2=
=A0is that he owns 9.6% of Twitter=E2=80=99s stock. Or, at least, he owned =
9.6% of the stock as of Friday. On Friday he sent Twitter a letter purporti=
ng to terminate the merger agreement. The merger agreement includes a provi=
sion (section 6.2(d)) requiring Musk not to sell any of his shares before T=
witter=E2=80=99s shareholder vote on the merger, but if Musk really believe=
s that he has terminated the merger agreement (risky!) then I suppose he ca=
n sell the shares, and honestly it would be hilarious if he did. If he does=
 sell any shares, he would have to disclose that =E2=80=9Cpromptly,=E2=80=
=9D which=C2=A0presumably means within a day or so. Is it possible that he =
started dumping his stock yesterday, and will disclose that this afternoon?=
 I suppose it is technically possible, and would be amazing. (Is it possibl=
e that he started dumping his stock yesterday and will file the report late=
?  That is also possible!
  [1]
)
Assuming, though, that he still owns 73.1 million shares of Twitter, and th=
at he does not want to sell those shares before a court decides if the deal=
 is off or not, then=C2=A0those shares are an interesting bargaining chip f=
or a settlement. Musk paid=C2=A0about $2.6 billion for those 73.1 million s=
hares, an average price of about $36.16 per share. The stock closed yesterd=
ay at $32.65, making his stake worth about $2.4 billion, for a loss of abou=
t $250 million.=C2=A0
If Musk and Twitter fight to the death over this deal, and Musk wins in cou=
rt and is able to get out of the deal for a $1 billion (or zero!) breakup f=
ee, then the stock will go down a lot. If he waits until then to sell, then=
 he might clear, I dunno, $25 per share, for a loss of about $800 million. =
Meanwhile Musk=E2=80=99s own selling will push down the stock, which will b=
e embarrassing for Twitter, which in this scenario will want to save face a=
nd preserve a shred of shareholder value. Musk will not want to sell his st=
ock into the market, but he will not want to hold it; Twitter will not want=
 him to sell his stock into the market, but will not want him as a sharehol=
der.
So there is some compromise where Twitter buys the stock directly=C2=A0from=
 Musk at =E2=80=94=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know, $26? =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Musk =
and Twitter are both better off than he would be if he dumped the stock int=
o the market.
Now, this trade doesn=E2=80=99t really work on its own. (Twitter can=E2=80=
=99t really buy stock from Musk at a premium.) But the trick is to combine =
it with a broader settlement. The deal is like:
=09Musk hands all his stock over to Twitter.=09Twitter pays Musk $0 for the=
 stock.=09Maybe Musk pays Twitter $X in cash, where X could be positive or =
zero or I guess even negative.=09Twitter says =E2=80=9CMusk paid us [$X in =
cash plus] $2.6 billion worth of stock, measured by his purchase price,=E2=
=80=9D even though the stock is only worth $1.8 billion or whatever as of t=
he time he hands it over. (Or =E2=80=9CMusk paid us $4 billion worth of sto=
ck, measured by the $54.20 deal price,=E2=80=9D why not?)

Twitter gets a face-saving headline settlement amount, gets rid of Musk, an=
d doesn=E2=80=99t have him dumping his stock in the market to depress the s=
tock; Musk gets to pay that settlement amount in discounted currency and ge=
ts out of the stock without pushing down the price.

