   =20
      VC value add
   =20
 =20

Here is a fun paper called =E2=80=9CPredictably Bad Investments: Evidence f=
rom Venture Capitalists,=E2=80=9D by Diag Davenport of the University of Ch=
icago=E2=80=99s Booth business school:
Do institutional investors invest efficiently? To study this question I com=
bine a novel dataset of over 16,000 startups (representing over $9 billion =
in investments) with machine learning methods to evaluate the decisions of =
early-stage investors. By comparing investor choices to an algorithm=E2=80=
=99s predictions, I show that approximately half of the investments were pr=
edictably bad=E2=80=94based on information known at the time of investment,=
 the predicted return of the investment was less than readily available out=
side options. The cost of these poor investments is 1000 basis points, tota=
lling over $900 million in my data. I provide suggestive evidence that over=
-reliance on the founders=E2=80=99 background is one mechanism underlying t=
hese choices. Together the results suggest that high stakes and firm sophis=
tication are not sufficient for efficient use of information in capital all=
ocation decisions.
Davenport finds =E2=80=9Cthat a standard off-the-shelf algorithm can strong=
ly discern between startups that are more or less likely to have exits.=E2=
=80=9D He then trains another machine-learning algorithm to predict =E2=80=
=9Ca different outcome: will the startup receive an early-stage investment.=
=E2=80=9D Actually he builds two of those: one to predict, effectively, if =
a=C2=A0bad=C2=A0startup (one that won=E2=80=99t have a profitable exit) wil=
l receive an early-stage investment, and another to predict if a=C2=A0good=
=C2=A0startup will get investors. Those models turn out to look for differe=
nt things:

The model trained on the worst firms appears to prioritize founder details,=
 whereas the model trained on the best firms appears to prioritize product =
details. When making good investments, investors appear to bet on the horse=
, but when making bad investments they appear to be betting on the jockey. =
...
Hit TV shows such as =E2=80=9DShark Tank=E2=80=9D and industry norms around=
 =E2=80=9DPitch Day=E2=80=9D events suggest an ethos built around founder c=
harisma and personal persuasion. In his best-selling book =E2=80=9DGood to =
Great=E2=80=9D, Collins (2009) asserts =E2=80=9CFirst Who, Then What=E2=80=
=9D and the idea has been absorbed into the zeitgeist. The ubiquity of this=
 perspective is a true success story of =E2=80=9Cmodel persuasion=E2=80=9D =
(Schwartzstein and Sunderam 2021). Investors seem convinced that the founde=
r-first model of the world is the correct one. This likely facilitates inve=
stors neglecting to notice features that are predictive and a feedback loop=
 of never noticing or learning persists, consistent with the model and evid=
ence presented in Hanna et al. (2014).

Let me make a general point here. Let=E2=80=99s say that you are a budding =
finance academic working on a Ph.D. at the University of Chicago. As part o=
f your thesis, you=C2=A0build an algorithm for evaluating companies, you ru=
n it on the companies in the S&P 500 Index, and you realize that if you use=
d the algorithm you could outperform the market by 10%. What do you do? I t=
hink the obvious answer is that you go to your professors, you show them th=
e research, they seed your fund, you delete=C2=A0your thesis, you drop out =
and run your strategy and make yourself and your professors rich. You use y=
our algorithm to buy the good stocks and avoid the bad stocks and outperfor=
m the market by 10%. I assume that if you go to Chicago and you find a way =
to beat the market by 10% and you=C2=A0publish=C2=A0it, they will not give =
you your Ph.D. This is Chicago! They have standards to uphold.=C2=A0They=E2=
=80=99re not gonna let you go out and put $10 bills on the sidewalk.
But this paper is about=C2=A0venture capital, and you can=E2=80=99t just go=
 out and run your algorithm on venture capital investments. Like, your algo=
rithm might tell you with perfect clarity which startups will do well and w=
hich will fail, and you can say =E2=80=9Cwell then I will just buy these st=
artups and avoid those,=E2=80=9D but you can=E2=80=99t actually do that. No=
ne of the startups =E2=80=94=C2=A0certainly not the good ones =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0are asking you for money. They=E2=80=99re asking venture capitalists for=
 money. Private markets are  importantly different from public markets. If =
you think of a better way to do public-market investing, you can just do it=
. The stocks are public, you can buy the good ones and avoid the bad ones. =
Private markets do not work that way. You can only buy the stocks that you=
=E2=80=99re invited to buy.
At this point I think it is conventional wisdom that the value added by ven=
ture capitalists is not=C2=A0picking the right companies=C2=A0but rather=C2=
=A0getting access to the best deals. (So much so that Tiger Global became a=
 late-stage-venture giant through a strategy of overpaying for everything w=
ithout doing much due diligence: If you get a reputation for doing that, th=
en everyone will invite you into their deals, so you will get the best deal=
 flow, and then you don=E2=80=99t have to care about picking the best compa=
nies because that is assumed not to be the job. This did not work out=C2=A0=
great, really, but I will hold off judgment until I know more about how tra=
ditional VCs did in this downturn.)
This paper provides some support for that conventional wisdom: In fact, Dav=
enport argues, venture capitalists=C2=A0aren=E2=80=99t great at picking the=
 right companies; they make predictable mistakes. But they still outperform=
=C2=A0public-market indexes, since they get access to good early-stage comp=
anies and the successes make up for those misses.
One way to read that is: Yes, but they should outperform by more, by gettin=
g access to companies and then picking the good ones. If this is your readi=
ng, then you (or Davenport) should go start a venture capital fund running =
his model, and outperform the other VCs. Or he should just sell his model t=
o VC firms so they can get better returns.
But another reading might be: Yes, but the VC funds=C2=A0have to=C2=A0inves=
t in the bad companies=C2=A0in order to=C2=A0get access to the good ones. I=
 don=E2=80=99t quite know how this would work. (To be clear, it=E2=80=99s n=
ot =E2=80=9Cthey have to buy the bad ones to get the good ones because you =
can=E2=80=99t tell ex ante which is which=E2=80=9D: Davenport says you=C2=
=A0can=C2=A0tell ex ante.) But it could work something like: =E2=80=9CFound=
ers choose their venture capital investors through some sort of reputationa=
l network; they talk to their founder buddies about which VCs are helpful a=
nd good to work with. If a VC rejects too many Stanford-dropout founders by=
 saying =E2=80=98sorry my algo says that your company is bad,=E2=80=99 then=
 the Stanford-dropout founders with=C2=A0good=C2=A0companies will hear abou=
t that from their Stanford-dropout ffriends, and won=E2=80=99t want to work=
 with that=C2=A0VC. Making bad investments is a way to be part of the club,=
 and being part of the club gets you the deal flow that gives you the good =
investments.=E2=80=9D

