#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">about $2.6 billion</a> for those 73.1 million shares, an average price of=
 about $36.16 per share. The stock closed yesterday at $32.65, making his s=
take worth about $2.4 billion, for a loss of about $250 million.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If Musk and Twitter fight to the death over th=
is deal, and Musk wins in court and is able to get out of the deal for a $1=
 billion (or zero!) breakup fee, then the stock will go down a lot. If he w=
aits until then to sell, then he might clear, I dunno, $25 per share, for a=
 loss of about $800 million. Meanwhile Musk=E2=80=99s own selling will push=
 down the stock, which will be embarrassing for Twitter, which in this scen=
ario will want to save face and preserve a shred of shareholder value. Musk=
 will not want to sell his stock into the market, but he will not want to h=
old it; Twitter will not want him to sell his stock into the market, but wi=
ll not want him as a shareholder.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So there is some compromise where Twitter buys=
 the stock directly=C2=A0from Musk at =E2=80=94=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know, =
$26? =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Musk and Twitter are both better off than he would =
be if he dumped the stock into the market.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, this trade doesn=E2=80=99t really work on=
 its own. (Twitter can=E2=80=99t really <em>buy stock from Musk at a premiu=
m</em>.) But the trick is to combine it with a broader settlement. The deal=
 is like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Musk hands all his stock over to Twit=
ter.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Twitter pays Musk $0 for the =
stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Maybe Musk pays Twitter $X =
in cash, where X could be positive or zero or I guess even negative.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Twitter says =E2=80=9CMusk paid us [$X=
 in cash plus] $2.6 billion worth of stock, measured by his purchase price,=
=E2=80=9D even though the stock is only worth $1.8 billion or whatever as o=
f the time he hands it over. (Or =E2=80=9CMusk paid us $4 billion worth of =
stock, measured by the $54.20 deal price,=E2=80=9D why not?)</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Twitter gets a face-saving headline settlement=
 amount, gets rid of Musk, and doesn=E2=80=99t have him dumping his stock i=
n the market to depress the stock; Musk gets to pay that settlement amount =
in discounted currency and gets out of the stock without pushing down the p=
rice.</p>
