<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a fun paper called =E2=80=9C<a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28351521.280590/aHR0cHM6Ly9w=
YXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQxMzU4NjE/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBad93505d/email" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Predictably Bad Investments: Evid=
ence from Venture Capitalists</a>,=E2=80=9D by Diag Davenport of the Univer=
sity of Chicago=E2=80=99s Booth business school:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Do institutional investors invest =
efficiently? To study this question I combine a novel dataset of over 16,00=
0 startups (representing over $9 billion in investments) with machine learn=
ing methods to evaluate the decisions of early-stage investors. By comparin=
g investor choices to an algorithm=E2=80=99s predictions, I show that appro=
ximately half of the investments were predictably bad=E2=80=94based on info=
rmation known at the time of investment, the predicted return of the invest=
ment was less than readily available outside options. The cost of these poo=
r investments is 1000 basis points, totalling over $900 million in my data.=
 I provide suggestive evidence that over-reliance on the founders=E2=80=99 =
background is one mechanism underlying these choices. Together the results =
suggest that high stakes and firm sophistication are not sufficient for eff=
icient use of information in capital allocation decisions.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Davenport finds =E2=80=9Cthat a standard off-t=
he-shelf algorithm can strongly discern between startups that are more or l=
ess likely to have exits.=E2=80=9D He then trains another machine-learning =
algorithm to predict =E2=80=9Ca different outcome: will the startup receive=
 an early-stage investment.=E2=80=9D Actually he builds two of those: one t=
o predict, effectively, if a=C2=A0<em>bad=C2=A0</em>startup (one that won=
=E2=80=99t have a profitable exit) will receive an early-stage investment, =
and another to predict if a=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>startup will get invest=
ors. Those models turn out to look for different things:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The model trained on the worst firms appears t=
o prioritize founder details, whereas the model trained on the best firms a=
ppears to prioritize product details. When making good investments, investo=
rs appear to bet on the horse, but when making bad investments they appear =
to be betting on the jockey. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hit TV shows such as =E2=80=9DShark Tank=E2=80=
=9D and industry norms around =E2=80=9DPitch Day=E2=80=9D events suggest an=
 ethos built around founder charisma and personal persuasion. In his best-s=
elling book =E2=80=9DGood to Great=E2=80=9D, Collins (2009) asserts =E2=80=
=9CFirst Who, Then What=E2=80=9D and the idea has been absorbed into the ze=
itgeist. The ubiquity of this perspective is a true success story of =E2=80=
=9Cmodel persuasion=E2=80=9D (Schwartzstein and Sunderam 2021). Investors s=
eem convinced that the founder-first model of the world is the correct one.=
 This likely facilitates investors neglecting to notice features that are p=
redictive and a feedback loop of never noticing or learning persists, consi=
stent with the model and evidence presented in Hanna et al. (2014).</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let me make a general point here. Let=E2=80=99=
s say that you are a budding finance academic working on a Ph.D. at the Uni=
versity of Chicago. As part of your thesis, you=C2=A0build an algorithm for=
 evaluating companies, you run it on the companies in the S&amp;P 500 Index=
, and you realize that if you used the algorithm you could outperform the m=
arket by 10%. What do you do? I think the obvious answer is that you go to =
your professors, you show them the research, they seed your fund, you delet=
e=C2=A0your thesis, you drop out and run your strategy and make yourself an=
d your professors rich. You use your algorithm to buy the good stocks and a=
void the bad stocks and outperform the market by 10%. I assume that if you =
go to Chicago and you find a way to beat the market by 10% and you=C2=A0<em=
>publish=C2=A0</em>it, they will not give you your Ph.D. This is Chicago! T=
hey have standards to uphold.=C2=A0They=E2=80=99re not gonna let you go out=
 and put $10 bills on the sidewalk.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this paper is about=C2=A0<em>venture capit=
al</em>, and you can=E2=80=99t just go out and run your algorithm on ventur=
e capital investments. Like, your algorithm might tell you with perfect cla=
rity which startups will do well and which will fail, and you can say =E2=
=80=9Cwell then I will just buy these startups and avoid those,=E2=80=9D bu=
t you can=E2=80=99t actually do that. None of the startups =E2=80=94=C2=A0c=
ertainly not the good ones =E2=80=94=C2=A0are asking you for money. They=E2=
=80=99re asking venture capitalists for money. Private markets are <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28351521.280590/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDYtMTkvcHJpdmF0ZS1t=
YXJrZXRzLWNvdWxkLWJlLW1vcmUtcHVibGljP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA3MTIyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV=
0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDcxMiZ1dG=
1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBae0bc432/email" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> importantly different from public markets</a>. If you think of a better=
 way to do public-market investing, you can just do it. The stocks are publ=
ic, you can buy the good ones and avoid the bad ones. Private markets do no=
t work that way. You can only buy the stocks that you=E2=80=99re invited to=
 buy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At this point I think it is conventional wisdo=
m that the value added by venture capitalists is not=C2=A0<em>picking the r=
ight companies=C2=A0</em>but rather=C2=A0<em>getting access to the best dea=
ls</em>. (So much so that Tiger Global became a late-stage-venture giant th=
rough <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28351521.280=
590/aHR0cHM6Ly9yYW5kbGUuc3Vic3RhY2suY29tL3AvcGxheWluZy1kaWZmZXJlbnQtZ2FtZXM=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa617fef4/email" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a strategy</a> of overpa=
ying for everything without doing much due diligence: If you get a reputati=
on for doing that, then everyone will invite you into their deals, so you w=
ill get the best deal flow, and then you don=E2=80=99t have to care about p=
icking the best companies because that is assumed not to be the job. This d=
id not work out=C2=A0<em>great</em>, really, but I will hold off judgment u=
ntil I know more about how traditional VCs did in this downturn.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This paper provides some support for that conv=
entional wisdom: In fact, Davenport argues, venture capitalists=C2=A0aren=
=E2=80=99t great at picking the right companies; they make predictable mist=
akes. But they still outperform=C2=A0public-market indexes, since they get =
access to good early-stage companies and the successes make up for those mi=
sses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to read that is: Yes, but they should =
outperform by more, by getting access to companies and then picking the goo=
d ones. If this is your reading, then you (or Davenport) should go start a =
venture capital fund running his model, and outperform the other VCs. Or he=
 should just sell his model to VC firms so they can get better returns.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But another reading might be: Yes, but the VC =
funds=C2=A0<em>have to=C2=A0</em>invest in the bad companies=C2=A0<em>in or=
der to=C2=A0</em>get access to the good ones. I don=E2=80=99t quite know ho=
w this would work. (To be clear, it=E2=80=99s not =E2=80=9Cthey have to buy=
 the bad ones to get the good ones because you can=E2=80=99t tell ex ante w=
hich is which=E2=80=9D: Davenport says you=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>tell ex a=
nte.) But it could work something like: =E2=80=9CFounders choose their vent=
ure capital investors through some sort of reputational network; they talk =
to their founder buddies about which VCs are helpful and good to work with.=
 If a VC rejects too many Stanford-dropout founders by saying =E2=80=98sorr=
y my algo says that your company is bad,=E2=80=99 then the Stanford-dropout=
 founders with=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>companies will hear about that from =
their Stanford-dropout ffriends, and won=E2=80=99t want to work with that=
=C2=A0VC. Making bad investments is a way to be part of the club, and being=
 part of the club gets you the deal flow that gives you the good investment=
s.=E2=80=9D</p>
